{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641826"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17910"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17910"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.08,0.27,0.19,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76898"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10624"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17910"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"10139"},{"type":"tags","id":"10770"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76898"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes is the biggest challenge in Australia\u2019s health system. It is the seventh most common cause of death by disease in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the first event in the natural history of type 2 diabetes mellitus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Development of insulin resistance","Beta cell dysfunction","Impaired glucose tolerance","Increasing adiposity","Hyperinsulinaemia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe development of type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2D) is a complex process that involves multiple metabolic changes. The first detectable abnormality in the natural history of T2D is the \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelopment of insulin resistance\u003C/strong\u003E. Insulin resistance occurs when cells in the body become less responsive to the action of insulin, leading to higher levels of insulin being required to maintain normal glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing adiposity\u003C/strong\u003E is a significant risk factor for insulin resistance and T2D, but it is not the first event in the disease\u0027s natural history. It contributes to the development of insulin resistance through various mechanisms, including the release of adipokines and inflammatory cytokines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperinsulinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs as a compensatory response to insulin resistance. The pancreas produces more insulin to overcome the resistance and maintain normal blood glucose levels. This is not the initial event but follows the development of insulin resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta cell dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E occurs later in the progression of T2D. Over time, the beta cells in the pancreas are unable to produce sufficient insulin to overcome insulin resistance, leading to hyperglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired glucose tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E is a prediabetic state characterised by higher than normal blood glucose levels after eating. It occurs after insulin resistance and beta cell dysfunction have developed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2D) is characterised by a progressive decline in insulin sensitivity and beta-cell function.","Insulin resistance is often the first detectable abnormality in the development of T2D.","Increased adiposity contributes to insulin resistance and is a significant risk factor for T2D."],"references":["Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Diabetes Australia. Diabetes in Australia [Internet]. Diabetes Australia. 2024. Available from: https://www.diabetesaustralia.com.au/about-diabetes/diabetes-in-australia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17910"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T19:45:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T19:46:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10624"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76898"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a